ed over time. Jeffrey K. Olick asserts that other nations are looking to Germany as an example of how a society can confront a dark past—casting Germany as our model of difficult collective memory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCollective memoryzGermany (West)xHistory. 0aGuilt and culturezGermany (West) 0aGuilt and culturezGermany (West). 0aNationalism and collective memoryzGermany (West) 0aNationalism and collective memoryzGermany (West). 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aGermany.  aWold War I.  aWorld War II.  acollective guilt.  acollective memory.  asociology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022638649240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226386522423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226386522/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles